"&#xa0;\nWritten evidence submitted by Marine Conservation Society&#xa0;Th\ne Marine Conservation Society (\nMCS) is the \nUK\n charity dedicated to the protection of the \nUK\n’s seas, shores and wildlife. \nMCS\n campaigns for clean seas and beaches, sustainable fisheries, protection of marine life and their habitats, and the sensitive use of our marine resources for future generations. \nMCS\n produces the annual Good Beach Guide, the Good Fish Guide on sustainable seafood, organises volunteer projects and surveys such as \nBeachwatch\n, the \nBeachwatch\n Big Weekend and Basking Shark Watch and works closely with the UK Government and devolved administrations on the development and implementation of marine laws and policies.\nMCS is a core member of the Break the \nB\nag \nH\nabit coalition that\n includes The Campaign to Protect Rural England, Keep Britain Tidy, Surfers Against Sewage, Thames 21 and Greener upon Thames. The coalition \nhas been campaigning for a charge on all single use carrier bags.  \nSummary&#xa0;\nImpacts of plastic bags Changes in bag usage following other UK schemes&#xa0;Impacts on budgets/jobsProposed Exemptions for EnglandExemptions of certain bag types \n‘\nBiodegradable’ bags \nPaper bags &#xa0;References(1)\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nDefra (2013). Paragraphs 10 and 60. Single-Use Plastic Bag Charge for \nEngland\n.\n \nCall for Evidence. \n&#xa0;\n(2)\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nMarine Conservation Society (2013). \nBeachwatch\n Big Weekend 2012: methods and results.\n&#xa0;\n(3)\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nMüller\n, C., Townsend, K. \nMatschullat\n, J. (2012) Experimental degradation of polymer shopping bags (standard and degradable plastic and biodegradable) in the gastrointestinal fluids of sea turtles. Science of the Total Environment. Volume 416: 464-467\n.\n \n(4)\n&#xa0;&#xa0;&#xa0; \nO’Brine\n, T., Thompson, R.C.\n(2010) \n Degradation of plastic carrier bags in the marine environment. Mar. \nPollut\n. Bull. (2010),\n \ndoi:10.1016/j.marpolbu